{"title_page": "Hunters (2020 TV series)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Hunters\n| image                    = Hunters (2020 TV series).png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Crime drama]]\n| creator                  = David Weil\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Logan Lerman]]\n* [[Jerrika Hinton]]\n* [[Lena Olin]]\n* [[Saul Rubinek]]\n* [[Carol Kane]]\n* [[Josh Radnor]]\n* [[Greg Austin (actor)|Greg Austin]]\n* [[Tiffany Boone]]\n* [[Louis Ozawa Changchien|Louis Ozawa]]\n* [[Kate Mulvany]]\n* [[Dylan Baker]]\n* [[Al Pacino]]\n}}\n| composer                 = [[Cristobal Tapia de Veer]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!-- Increment when new seasons/series begin -->\n| num_episodes             = 10<!-- Value is incremented when new episodes air. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Tom Lesinski\n* David Ellender\n* Jenna Santoianni\n* Win Rosenfeld\n* [[Nelson McCormick (director)|Nelson McCormick]]\n* Alfonso Gomez-Rejon\n* David Weil\n* Nikki Toscano\n* [[Jordan Peele]]\n* David J. Rosen\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jerry Kupfer]]\n* Kris Baucom\n* [[Glenn Kessler (screenwriter)|Glenn Kessler]]\n* Mark Bianculli\n}}\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| runtime                  = 57\u201390 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Monkeypaw Productions]]}}\n* [[Sonar Entertainment]]\n* Big Indie\n* Black Mass Productions\n* Governor's Court\n* [[Amazon Studios]]\n}}\n| network                  = [[Amazon Prime Video]]\n| first_aired              = February 21, 2020\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = \n| theme_music_composer     = Trevor Gureckis\n}}\n\n'''''Hunters''''' is an American [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[web television]] series created by David Weil. It premiered on February 21, 2020, on [[Amazon Prime Video]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Video: Amazon Original \"Hunters\" Debuts Tease for Upcoming Series Starring Al Pacino and Logan Lerman|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/video/2019/11/01/video-amazon-original-hunters-debuts-tease-for-upcoming-series-starring-al-pacino-and-logan-lerman-436510/20191101amazon01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amazon Prime Video Sets February 21 Debut for Al Pacino Conspiracy Thriller Series \"Hunters\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/01/03/amazon-prime-video-sets-february-21-debut-for-al-pacino-conspiracy-thriller-series-hunters-733011/20200103amazon01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/hunters-canceled-or-renewed-season-2-amazon-series-faces-new-controversy-2927517Is |title='Hunters' Canceled Or Renewed For Season 2? Amazon Series Faces New Controversy |work=International Business News}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series is inspired by a number of real [[Nazi hunter]]s through the decades, but it is not meant to be a specific representation of any of them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/2020/02/9456900/nazi-hunters-amazon-show-true-story-real-events |title=The True Story Behind Jordan Peele & Amazon's 1970s Conspiracy Thriller Hunters |first=Sarah |last=Midkiff |work=Refinery 29 |date=February 24, 2020 |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> It follows a diverse band of Nazi hunters living in 1977 [[New York City]] who discover that Nazi war criminals are conspiring to create a [[Fourth Reich]] in the U.S.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Amazon Nabs Jordan Peele's Nazi Hunters Drama With Series Order, Sonar Produces|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/amazon-jordan-peele-nazi-hunters-drama-series-order-sonar-produces-1202392859/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref> A parallel plot element is the discovery of [[Operation Paperclip]], the U.S. government operation relocating many German scientists (many of them Nazis) to the U.S.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n*[[Al Pacino]] as Meyer Offerman, a Polish-Jewish philanthropist and Holocaust survivor who recruits and leads the Hunters.\n**Zack Schor as young Meyer\n*[[Logan Lerman]] as Jonah Heidelbaum, a young mathematics whiz who takes his grandmother's place on the Hunters\n*[[Lena Olin]] as [[Eva Braun|The Colonel]], leader of the Fourth Reich\n*[[Jerrika Hinton]] as Millie Morris, an FBI agent who stumbles onto the Fourth Reich and the Hunters during a murder investigation\n*[[Saul Rubinek]] as Murray Markowitz, Mindy's husband and the Hunters' electronics expert. A German-Jewish Holocaust survivor. \n*[[Carol Kane]] as Mindy Markowitz, Murray's wife and the Hunters' signals expert. A German-Jewish Holocaust survivor.\n*[[Josh Radnor]] as Lonny Flash, actor and master of disguises for the Hunters\n*[[Greg Austin (actor)|Greg Austin]] as Travis Leich, a Nazi acolyte drawn into the Fourth Reich\n*[[Tiffany Boone]] as Roxy Jones, the Hunters' driver and first fighter\n*[[Louis Ozawa Changchien|Louis Ozawa]] as Joe Mizushima, a [[Vietnam War]] veteran and the Hunters' combat expert\n*[[Kate Mulvany]] as Sister Harriet, a former [[MI6]] operative who now works with the Hunters. A former German-Jewish child refugee\n*[[Dylan Baker]] as Biff Simpson, an Undersecretary of State in the [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]] administration and secretly an undercover Nazi agent.\n\n===Recurring===\n*[[Christian Oliver]] as Wilhelm Zuchs, \"The Wolf,\" a Nazi doctor at Auschwitz who tormented both Meyer and Jonah's grandmother Ruth\n*[[Victor Williams]] as Detective Kennedy Groton\n*[[Jonno Davies]] as Tobias, the Colonel's body man\n*[[James LeGros]] as Hank Grimsby, former [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]] operative and now Millie's boss at the FBI\n*[[Ebony Obsidian]] as Carol Lockhart\n*Caleb Emery as Arthur \"Bootyhole\" McGuigan\n*[[Henry Hunter Hall]] as Sherman \"Cheeks\" Johnson\n*[[Jeannie Berlin]] as Ruth Heidelbaum, Jonah's grandmother and a survivor of Auschwitz\n**Annie H\u00e4gg as young Ruth\n*[[Julissa Bermudez]] as Maria, Millie's girlfriend and a nurse\n*Phoenix Noelle as Malika\n*Megan Channell as Katarina L\u00f6w\n*'Keena' Thort-Kourt Kyna Kynetruve as the Great Dane\n*Miles G. Jackson as Danny Rohr\n*[[Becky Ann Baker]] as Commerce Secretary [[Juanita M. Kreps]]\n*[[Celia Weston]] as Dottie\n*Ben Livingston as President [[Jimmy Carter]]\n*Hannah Reid Rubinek, Saul Rubinek's real-life daughter, as Amy Markowitz\nJoshua Satine as Aaron Markowitz\n\n===Guests===\n*[[Josh Mostel]] as Rabbi Steckler\n*[[Barbara Sukowa]] as Tilda Sauer\n*June Ballinger as Woman with Cane\n*[[Judd Hirsch]] as [[Simon Wiesenthal]]\n*[[Keir Dullea]] as Klaus Rhinehart\n*[[William Sadler (actor)|William Sadler]] as Friedrich Mann\n*[[John Noble]] as Fredric Hauser\n*[[Victor Slezak]] as [[Wernher Von Braun]]\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#F4CA16 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=Hunters \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/hunters/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref> |released=y |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = In the Belly of the Whale\n |DirectedBy      = [[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]]<ref name=\"TFC\"/>\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = US undersecretary of state Biff hosts a barbecue, where a guest is shocked to remember him as a senior Nazi, leading to Biff killing all present, including his own family. Jonah witnesses the brutal murder of his grandmother inside their Brooklyn home, and subsequently vows to find the truth of her death. He meets Ruth\u2019s old friend, Meyer Offerman, while sitting Shiva for Ruth. In Florida, an elderly [[NASA]] scientist is killed in her shower. Jonah, who is a code-breaking prodigy, sees just a few clues in Meyer's home, but uses them to find Ruth's killer \u2014 a toy-shop owner who was a murderous guard at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] and the killer of Ruth's younger sister. The toy-shop owner gets the upper hand, but Meyer arrives and kills him.   \n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = The Mourner's Kaddish\n |DirectedBy      = [[Wayne Yip]]\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Meyer brings Jonah into the Hunters, who are initially reluctant to have him involved, though he quickly gains some acceptance by breaking a code in the toy maker's correspondence. Jonah learns that Ruth was a major part of the Hunters, having built their extensive archive of historical files and more recent interviews. FBI agent Millie, investigating the death of the scientist, starts to uncover the Nazi links. Travis, a deadly American born Nazi working for The Colonel, who is leading the Nazi underground, is sent to Florida to learn who is killing their members. The Hunters track down a record producer who used to be the murderous Pied Piper of [[Buchenwald concentration camp]]. The Hunters find seemingly innocuous messages the man is secretly broadcasting, but Jonah messes up and the man is killed before they can learn more.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = While Visions of Safta Danced in His Head\n |DirectedBy      = Wayne Yip\n |WrittenBy       = Nikki Toscano\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Markowitzes discover a code in the Pied Piper's broadcasts, suggesting that tragic events in America's past, including the [[Watergate scandal]] and the [[assassination of RFK]], were part of a Nazi plot. The messages suggest the next big Nazi-managed event will take place on [[New York City blackout of 1977|July 13, 1977]] in New York. Jonah's friend Bootyhole, who was working in the comic book store instead of Jonah, is killed by Travis.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = The Pious Thieves\n |DirectedBy      = [[Nelson McCormick (director)|Nelson McCormick]]\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Bianculli\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Hunters find a huge collection of Nazi stolen treasure hidden in a bank in New Jersey. Jonah finds letters written by Ruth, explaining the deepening affection between her and Meyer while at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]].\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = At Night, All Birds are Black\n |DirectedBy      = [[Dennie Gordon]]\n |WrittenBy       = David J. Rosen\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = At Auschwitz concentration camp, a doctor known as The Wolf is disappointed when Ruth will not work with him, so he does tortuous experiments on Meyer in retaliation. Half the Hunters goes to Alabama to pursue a Nazi doctor who experimented on prisoners during the war, while the others go after Tilda, a Nazi propaganda film director now working as a political consultant. Millie continues pursuing her own leads on the presence of Nazis in America. Unknown assailants (Nazis? FBI protecting the Nazis?) beat up Millie. Sister Harriet rescues a Nazi from the others and drives off.  \n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = (Ruth 1:16)\n |DirectedBy      = [[Millicent Shelton]]\n |WrittenBy       = Zakiyyah Alexander\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The day of the Markowitz' daughter's wedding, Murray recalls how they were taken, with their young son, to be sent to a concentration camp, where an officer killed their son. Flashbacks show that Sister Harriet was secretly sent to England, with other young German girls, to hide out during the war. She arrives at the wedding, revealing that she has tied up the Nazi, who she had realized was the man who killed the Markowitz boy. Millie breaks up with her live-in girlfriend, fearing she will be attacked too. Travis breaks into Meyer's mansion and is able to burn many of the files the Hunters are using to track Nazis.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = Shalom Motherf***er\n |DirectedBy      = Nelson McCormick\n |WrittenBy       = Eduardo Javier Canto & Ryan Maldonado\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Meyer admits that he is Jonah's grandfather. Morris, despite knowing that the recent victims are Nazis who murdered millions, is hellbent on charging Offerman with murder, misleading a judge in order to get a warrant to arrest Offerman. When Jonah solves the final piece of the Nazi music code, the Hunters discover a Nazi plot to sneak a shipment of a biological weapon through the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|port of New York]] by causing distractions with the [[New York City blackout of 1977]] and bombing a crowded [[New York City Subway|subway car]]. Murray and Jonah save the passengers, but Murray Markowitz is killed trying to disarm the bomb.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = The Jewish Question\n |DirectedBy      = [[Michael Uppendahl]]\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil & Charley Casler\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Mindy Markowitz kills the man who murdered her son after burying Murray, who she was surprised to find out wanted a Jewish funeral when he finally died. Meyer tells Jonah why he and Ruth never married: at Auschwitz, Meyer chose to shoot a series of eleven prisoners in order to stop the Wolf from shooting Ruth, ignoring her pleas to let the Wolf shoot her instead. The Hunters find Nazi and NASA scientist [[Wernher von Braun]] via Nazi Hunter [[Simon Wiesenthal]], who is diametrically opposed to Meyer's team killing the Nazis rather than bringing them before legal tribunals.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = The Great Ole Nazi Cookout of '77\n |DirectedBy      = Nelson McCormick\n |WrittenBy       = Nikki Toscano\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The episode begins with a review of the reasons given for [[Operation Paperclip|bringing over the Nazis to the United States]] in the first place, so that the [[USSR]] would not be able to recruit them for their government and [[Soviet space program|space program]]. The Hunters attack the Fourth Reich's bunker, destroying it and the [[corn syrup]] carrying their pathogen before it can be released. During a struggle, Jonah has the chance to kill Travis, but is talked down by Morris who arrests Travis instead. Meyer manages to capture the Colonel who suggests that the pathogen isn't the Fourth Reich's only plan. A struggle ensues, causing Meyer to crash the car into the river.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Eilu v' Eilu\n |DirectedBy      = Michael Uppendahl\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Meyer is rescued from the wreck by Harriet while the Colonel is killed. Jonah begins a search for Wilhelm \"The Wolf\" Zuchs, the Nazi doctor who tortured Meyer and Ruth thirty years before. From clues, Jonah discovers Ruth's files which lead him to capture a surgeon he believes to be the Wolf who Meyer executes. However, Meyer doesn't recite a prayer he'd sworn to Ruth he would if he ever caught up to the Wolf, leading a horrified Jonah to put the pieces together and realize that Meyer is actually the Wolf. Zuchs confesses, explaining that he had killed the real Meyer to take his identity and escape the Soviets while later undergoing [[plastic surgery]] (from the SS surgeon he just now killed) to complete the transformation. Having lived a Jewish life for thirty years, Zuchs insists that he regrets his actions and that a visit by Ruth a year before inspired him to bring the Hunters together as penance. Despite a vision of Ruth attempting to talk him down, Jonah kills Zuchs and reveals the truth to the other horrified Hunters. Harriet, after having consulted with an unidentified woman, suggests to the remaining Hunters that they continue their mission in Europe. Mizushima is kidnapped and taken to [[National Reorganization Process|Argentina]], where he discovers that The Colonel is alive, her identity is [[Eva Braun]] and she is living with [[Adolf Hitler]] and four identical Aryan-looking boys.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn May 17, 2018, it was announced that [[Amazon Video]] had given the production a straight-to-series order for a first season consisting of ten episodes. The series was created by David Weil who was set to executive produce alongside [[Jordan Peele]], Tom Lesinski, Jenna Santoianni, and Win Rosenfeld. Weil was also expected to write for the series as well. Production companies involved with the series were slated to consist of [[Monkeypaw Productions]] and [[Sonar Entertainment]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Maas|first=Jennifer|title=Amazon Orders Jordan Peele's Nazi-Hunting Show to Series|url=https://www.thewrap.com/amazon-orders-jordan-peeles-nazi-hunting-show-series/|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Jordan Peele-Produced Nazi Hunter Drama Ordered to Series at Amazon|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/jordan-peele-produced-nazi-hunter-drama-ordered-to-series-at-amazon-1202813713/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|title=Jordan Peele Nazi Drama Picked Up to Series at Amazon|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jordan-peele-nazi-drama-picked-up-series-at-amazon-1112812|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref> On August 7, 2018, it was announced that Nikki Toscano had joined the production as an executive producer and would also serve as co-showrunner alongside Weil.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='The Hunt': Nikki Toscano Joins Jordan Peele's Nazi Hunters Amazon Series As EP|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/the-hunt-nikki-toscano-jordan-peele-nazi-hunters-amazon-drama-series-executive-producer-showrunner-1202432730/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn December 13, 2018, it was reported that [[Logan Lerman]] was in talks for a lead role in the series, Jonah Heidelbaum.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Logan Lerman In Talks For Lead In Jordan Peele's 'The Hunt' Amazon Drama Series|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/logan-lerman-in-talks-for-lead-in-jordan-peeles-the-hunt-amazon-drama-series-1202519900/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 13, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref> On January 10, 2019, it was reported that [[Al Pacino]] was finalizing a deal for a starring role in the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike Jr|title=Al Pacino Poised To Make TV Series Starring Debut In 'The Hunt'|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/al-pacino-television-series-star-debut-the-hunt-amazon-logan-lerman-1202532584/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 10, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> On February 7, 2019, it was reported that [[Jerrika Hinton]], [[Dylan Baker]], [[Lena Olin]], [[Greg Austin (actor)|Greg Austin]], [[Catherine Tate]], [[Tiffany Boone]], [[Saul Rubinek]], and [[Carol Kane]] were in various stages of negotiations to join the cast of the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Exclusive: Jordan Peele's Cast for Amazon's 'The Hunt' Takes Shape|url=https://collider.com/jordan-peele-the-hunt-supporting-cast/|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> Four days later, it was announced that Boone had officially joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title='The Hunt': Tiffany Boone Cast In Jordan Peele's Amazon Drama Series|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-hunt-tiffany-boone-cast-jordan-peeles-amazon-drama-series-1202554658/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> [[Josh Radnor]] was cast in March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-hunt-josh-radnor-cast-jordan-peele-amazon-drama-series-1202567664/ |title='The Hunt': Josh Radnor To Co-Star In Jordan Peele's Amazon Drama Series |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> In April 2019, [[Kate Mulvany]], [[James LeGros]], [[Ebony Obsidian]],  Caleb Emery, Henry Hunter Hall and [[Jeannie Berlin]] joined the cast of the series, with Mulvany joining as a series regular.<ref>{{cite web|last=Day-Ramos|first=Dino|title='The Hunt' Adds Kate Mulvany As Series Regular, 5 More Join In Recurring Roles For Amazon Original|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/the-hunt-kate-mulvany-series-regular-amazon-jordan-peele-james-le-gros-ebony-obsidian-caleb-emery-henry-hunter-hall-jeannie-berline-david-weil-1202593377/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Hunters'' received polarizing reviews, with criticism for its tone and pacing and praise for its performances. The series has a 65% approval rating with 92 reviews on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average rating of 6.21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/hunters_2020/s01|title=''Hunters'': Season 1 (2020) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the series a score of 55 out of 100 based on 37 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/hunters-2020/season-1?ref=hp|title=''Hunters'': Season 1|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe series has received some criticism from the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]] due to inaccurate use of the [[Auschwitz Concentration Camp]]. The scene depicting prisoners being forced to participate in a game of human chess was called out as \"dangerous foolishness and caricature\". The museum was also concerned that the show \"welcomes future deniers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/02/23/amazon-hunters-criticized-by-auschwitz-memorial-museum/|title=Amazon drama Hunters criticized by Auschwitz Memorial Museum|last=Cordero|first=Rosy|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 23, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/amazon-hunters-david-weil-criticism-auschwitz-memorial-chess-nazis-1488714 |title=Amazon's 'Hunters' Creators Fictional Holocaust Atrocities Following Criticism From Auschwitz Memorial |work=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hunters-stars-ponder-moral-question-at-center-nazi-hunter-amazon-drama-1280317 |title='Hunters' Stars Ponder the Moral Question at the Center of Their Nazi Hunter Amazon Drama|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> Director of the [[USC Shoah Foundation]] [[Stephen D. Smith]] heavily criticized the show and concluded that \"Amazon must not renew it for a second season.\"<ref>Smith, Stephen.  [https://jewishjournal.com/columnist-2/312011/shoah-foundation-director-amazon-must-cancel-hunters/ Shoah Foundation Director: Amazon Must Cancel \u2018Hunters.\u2019\"] ''Jewish Journal''.  12 March 2020.  13 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|7456722}}\n*[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=HBGkjmfIzAw Trailer]\n\n{{Amazon Video original series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunters}}\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:Amazon Video original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Nazi hunters in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Television series set in 1977]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fascism in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Hunters\n| image                    = Hunters (2020 TV series).png\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = [[Crime drama]]\n| creator                  = David Weil\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Logan Lerman]]\n* [[Jerrika Hinton]]\n* [[Lena Olin]]\n* [[Saul Rubinek]]\n* [[Carol Kane]]\n* [[Josh Radnor]]\n* [[Greg Austin (actor)|Greg Austin]]\n* [[Tiffany Boone]]\n* [[Louis Ozawa Changchien|Louis Ozawa]]\n* [[Kate Mulvany]]\n* [[Dylan Baker]]\n* [[Al Pacino]]\n}}\n| composer                 = [[Cristobal Tapia de Veer]]\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 1<!-- Increment when new seasons/series begin -->\n| num_episodes             = 10<!-- Value is incremented when new episodes air. See template documentation for more info. -->\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Tom Lesinski\n* David Ellender\n* Jenna Santoianni\n* Win Rosenfeld\n* [[Nelson McCormick (director)|Nelson McCormick]]\n* Alfonso Gomez-Rejon\n* David Weil\n* Nikki Toscano\n* [[Jordan Peele]]\n* David J. Rosen\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jerry Kupfer]]\n* Kris Baucom\n* [[Glenn Kessler (screenwriter)|Glenn Kessler]]\n* Mark Bianculli\n}}\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| runtime                  = 57\u201390 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* {{nowrap|[[Monkeypaw Productions]]}}\n* [[Sonar Entertainment]]\n* Big Indie\n* Black Mass Productions\n* Governor's Court\n* [[Amazon Studios]]\n}}\n| network                  = [[Amazon Prime Video]]\n| first_aired              = February 21, 2020\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = \n| theme_music_composer     = Trevor Gureckis\n}}\n\n'''''Hunters''''' is an American [[Drama (film and television)|drama]] [[web television]] series created by David Weil. It premiered on February 21, 2020, on [[Amazon Prime Video]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Video: Amazon Original \"Hunters\" Debuts Tease for Upcoming Series Starring Al Pacino and Logan Lerman|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/video/2019/11/01/video-amazon-original-hunters-debuts-tease-for-upcoming-series-starring-al-pacino-and-logan-lerman-436510/20191101amazon01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=November 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amazon Prime Video Sets February 21 Debut for Al Pacino Conspiracy Thriller Series \"Hunters\"|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2020/01/03/amazon-prime-video-sets-february-21-debut-for-al-pacino-conspiracy-thriller-series-hunters-733011/20200103amazon01/|work=[[The Futon Critic]]|date=January 3, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/hunters-canceled-or-renewed-season-2-amazon-series-faces-new-controversy-2927517Is |title='Hunters' Canceled Or Renewed For Season 2? Amazon Series Faces New Controversy |work=International Business News}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series is inspired by a number of real [[Nazi hunter]]s through the decades, but it is not meant to be a specific representation of any of them.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-gb/2020/02/9456900/nazi-hunters-amazon-show-true-story-real-events |title=The True Story Behind Jordan Peele & Amazon's 1970s Conspiracy Thriller Hunters |first=Sarah |last=Midkiff |work=Refinery 29 |date=February 24, 2020 |access-date=February 25, 2020}}</ref> It follows a diverse band of Nazi hunters living in 1977 [[New York City]] who discover that Nazi war criminals are conspiring to create a [[Fourth Reich]] in the U.S.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\">{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Amazon Nabs Jordan Peele's Nazi Hunters Drama With Series Order, Sonar Produces|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/amazon-jordan-peele-nazi-hunters-drama-series-order-sonar-produces-1202392859/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref> A parallel plot element is the discovery of [[Operation Paperclip]], the U.S. government operation relocating many German scientists (many of them Nazis) to the U.S.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n*[[Al Pacino]] as Meyer Offerman, a Polish-Jewish philanthropist and Holocaust survivor who recruits and leads the Hunters.\n**Zack Schor as young Meyer\n*[[Logan Lerman]] as Jonah Heidelbaum, a young mathematics whiz who takes his grandmother's place on the Hunters\n*[[Lena Olin]] as [[Eva Braun|The Colonel]], leader of the Fourth Reich\n*[[Jerrika Hinton]] as Millie Morris, an FBI agent who stumbles onto the Fourth Reich and the Hunters during a murder investigation\n*[[Saul Rubinek]] as Murray Markowitz, Mindy's husband and the Hunters' electronics expert. A German-Jewish Holocaust survivor. \n*[[Carol Kane]] as Mindy Markowitz, Murray's wife and the Hunters' signals expert. A German-Jewish Holocaust survivor.\n*[[Josh Radnor]] as Lonny Flash, actor and master of disguises for the Hunters\n*[[Greg Austin (actor)|Greg Austin]] as Travis Leich, a Nazi acolyte drawn into the Fourth Reich\n*[[Tiffany Boone]] as Roxy Jones, the Hunters' driver and first fighter\n*[[Louis Ozawa Changchien|Louis Ozawa]] as Joe Mizushima, a [[Vietnam War]] veteran and the Hunters' combat expert\n*[[Kate Mulvany]] as Sister Harriet, a former [[MI6]] operative who now works with the Hunters. A former German-Jewish child refugee\n*[[Dylan Baker]] as Biff Simpson, an Undersecretary of State in the [[Jimmy Carter|Carter]] administration and secretly an undercover Nazi agent.\n\n===Recurring===\n*[[Christian Oliver]] as Wilhelm Zuchs, \"The Wolf,\" a Nazi doctor at Auschwitz who tormented both Meyer and Jonah's grandmother Ruth\n*[[Victor Williams]] as Detective Kennedy Groton\n*[[Jonno Davies]] as Tobias, the Colonel's body man\n*[[James LeGros]] as Hank Grimsby, former [[Office of Strategic Services|OSS]] operative and now Millie's boss at the FBI\n*[[Ebony Obsidian]] as Carol Lockhart\n*Caleb Emery as Arthur \"Bootyhole\" McGuigan\n*[[Henry Hunter Hall]] as Sherman \"Cheeks\" Johnson\n*[[Jeannie Berlin]] as Ruth Heidelbaum, Jonah's grandmother and a survivor of Auschwitz\n**Annie H\u00e4gg as young Ruth\n*[[Julissa Bermudez]] as Maria, Millie's girlfriend and a nurse\n*Phoenix Noelle as Malika\n*Megan Channell as Katarina L\u00f6w\n*'Keena' Thort-Kourt Kyna Kynetruve as the Great Dane\n*Miles G. Jackson as Danny Rohr\n*[[Becky Ann Baker]] as Commerce Secretary [[Juanita M. Kreps]]\n*[[Celia Weston]] as Dottie\n*Ben Livingston as President [[Jimmy Carter]]\n*Hannah Reid Rubinek, Saul Rubinek's real-life daughter, as Amy Markowitz\n\n===Guests===\n*[[Josh Mostel]] as Rabbi Steckler\n*[[Barbara Sukowa]] as Tilda Sauer\n*June Ballinger as Woman with Cane\n*[[Judd Hirsch]] as [[Simon Wiesenthal]]\n*[[Keir Dullea]] as Klaus Rhinehart\n*[[William Sadler (actor)|William Sadler]] as Friedrich Mann\n*[[John Noble]] as Fredric Hauser\n*[[Victor Slezak]] as [[Wernher Von Braun]]\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |background=#F4CA16 |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=Hunters \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/hunters/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref> |released=y |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n |Title           = In the Belly of the Whale\n |DirectedBy      = [[Alfonso Gomez-Rejon]]<ref name=\"TFC\"/>\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = US undersecretary of state Biff hosts a barbecue, where a guest is shocked to remember him as a senior Nazi, leading to Biff killing all present, including his own family. Jonah witnesses the brutal murder of his grandmother inside their Brooklyn home, and subsequently vows to find the truth of her death. He meets Ruth\u2019s old friend, Meyer Offerman, while sitting Shiva for Ruth. In Florida, an elderly [[NASA]] scientist is killed in her shower. Jonah, who is a code-breaking prodigy, sees just a few clues in Meyer's home, but uses them to find Ruth's killer \u2014 a toy-shop owner who was a murderous guard at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] and the killer of Ruth's younger sister. The toy-shop owner gets the upper hand, but Meyer arrives and kills him.   \n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 2\n |Title           = The Mourner's Kaddish\n |DirectedBy      = [[Wayne Yip]]\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Meyer brings Jonah into the Hunters, who are initially reluctant to have him involved, though he quickly gains some acceptance by breaking a code in the toy maker's correspondence. Jonah learns that Ruth was a major part of the Hunters, having built their extensive archive of historical files and more recent interviews. FBI agent Millie, investigating the death of the scientist, starts to uncover the Nazi links. Travis, a deadly American born Nazi working for The Colonel, who is leading the Nazi underground, is sent to Florida to learn who is killing their members. The Hunters track down a record producer who used to be the murderous Pied Piper of [[Buchenwald concentration camp]]. The Hunters find seemingly innocuous messages the man is secretly broadcasting, but Jonah messes up and the man is killed before they can learn more.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 3\n |Title           = While Visions of Safta Danced in His Head\n |DirectedBy      = Wayne Yip\n |WrittenBy       = Nikki Toscano\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Markowitzes discover a code in the Pied Piper's broadcasts, suggesting that tragic events in America's past, including the [[Watergate scandal]] and the [[assassination of RFK]], were part of a Nazi plot. The messages suggest the next big Nazi-managed event will take place on [[New York City blackout of 1977|July 13, 1977]] in New York. Jonah's friend Bootyhole, who was working in the comic book store instead of Jonah, is killed by Travis.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 4\n |Title           = The Pious Thieves\n |DirectedBy      = [[Nelson McCormick (director)|Nelson McCormick]]\n |WrittenBy       = Mark Bianculli\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The Hunters find a huge collection of Nazi stolen treasure hidden in a bank in New Jersey. Jonah finds letters written by Ruth, explaining the deepening affection between her and Meyer while at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]].\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 5\n |Title           = At Night, All Birds are Black\n |DirectedBy      = [[Dennie Gordon]]\n |WrittenBy       = David J. Rosen\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = At Auschwitz concentration camp, a doctor known as The Wolf is disappointed when Ruth will not work with him, so he does tortuous experiments on Meyer in retaliation. Half the Hunters goes to Alabama to pursue a Nazi doctor who experimented on prisoners during the war, while the others go after Tilda, a Nazi propaganda film director now working as a political consultant. Millie continues pursuing her own leads on the presence of Nazis in America. Unknown assailants (Nazis? FBI protecting the Nazis?) beat up Millie. Sister Harriet rescues a Nazi from the others and drives off.  \n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 6\n |Title           = (Ruth 1:16)\n |DirectedBy      = [[Millicent Shelton]]\n |WrittenBy       = Zakiyyah Alexander\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The day of the Markowitz' daughter's wedding, Murray recalls how they were taken, with their young son, to be sent to a concentration camp, where an officer killed their son. Flashbacks show that Sister Harriet was secretly sent to England, with other young German girls, to hide out during the war. She arrives at the wedding, revealing that she has tied up the Nazi, who she had realized was the man who killed the Markowitz boy. Millie breaks up with her live-in girlfriend, fearing she will be attacked too. Travis breaks into Meyer's mansion and is able to burn many of the files the Hunters are using to track Nazis.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 7\n |Title           = Shalom Motherf***er\n |DirectedBy      = Nelson McCormick\n |WrittenBy       = Eduardo Javier Canto & Ryan Maldonado\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Meyer admits that he is Jonah's grandfather. Morris, despite knowing that the recent victims are Nazis who murdered millions, is hellbent on charging Offerman with murder, misleading a judge in order to get a warrant to arrest Offerman. When Jonah solves the final piece of the Nazi music code, the Hunters discover a Nazi plot to sneak a shipment of a biological weapon through the [[Port of New York and New Jersey|port of New York]] by causing distractions with the [[New York City blackout of 1977]] and bombing a crowded [[New York City Subway|subway car]]. Murray and Jonah save the passengers, but Murray Markowitz is killed trying to disarm the bomb.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 8\n |Title           = The Jewish Question\n |DirectedBy      = [[Michael Uppendahl]]\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil & Charley Casler\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Mindy Markowitz kills the man who murdered her son after burying Murray, who she was surprised to find out wanted a Jewish funeral when he finally died. Meyer tells Jonah why he and Ruth never married: at Auschwitz, Meyer chose to shoot a series of eleven prisoners in order to stop the Wolf from shooting Ruth, ignoring her pleas to let the Wolf shoot her instead. The Hunters find Nazi and NASA scientist [[Wernher von Braun]] via Nazi Hunter [[Simon Wiesenthal]], who is diametrically opposed to Meyer's team killing the Nazis rather than bringing them before legal tribunals.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 9\n |Title           = The Great Ole Nazi Cookout of '77\n |DirectedBy      = Nelson McCormick\n |WrittenBy       = Nikki Toscano\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = The episode begins with a review of the reasons given for [[Operation Paperclip|bringing over the Nazis to the United States]] in the first place, so that the [[USSR]] would not be able to recruit them for their government and [[Soviet space program|space program]]. The Hunters attack the Fourth Reich's bunker, destroying it and the [[corn syrup]] carrying their pathogen before it can be released. During a struggle, Jonah has the chance to kill Travis, but is talked down by Morris who arrests Travis instead. Meyer manages to capture the Colonel who suggests that the pathogen isn't the Fourth Reich's only plan. A struggle ensues, causing Meyer to crash the car into the river.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 10\n |Title           = Eilu v' Eilu\n |DirectedBy      = Michael Uppendahl\n |WrittenBy       = David Weil\n |OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|21}}\n |ShortSummary    = Meyer is rescued from the wreck by Harriet while the Colonel is killed. Jonah begins a search for Wilhelm \"The Wolf\" Zuchs, the Nazi doctor who tortured Meyer and Ruth thirty years before. From clues, Jonah discovers Ruth's files which lead him to capture a surgeon he believes to be the Wolf who Meyer executes. However, Meyer doesn't recite a prayer he'd sworn to Ruth he would if he ever caught up to the Wolf, leading a horrified Jonah to put the pieces together and realize that Meyer is actually the Wolf. Zuchs confesses, explaining that he had killed the real Meyer to take his identity and escape the Soviets while later undergoing [[plastic surgery]] (from the SS surgeon he just now killed) to complete the transformation. Having lived a Jewish life for thirty years, Zuchs insists that he regrets his actions and that a visit by Ruth a year before inspired him to bring the Hunters together as penance. Despite a vision of Ruth attempting to talk him down, Jonah kills Zuchs and reveals the truth to the other horrified Hunters. Harriet, after having consulted with an unidentified woman, suggests to the remaining Hunters that they continue their mission in Europe. Mizushima is kidnapped and taken to [[National Reorganization Process|Argentina]], where he discovers that The Colonel is alive, her identity is [[Eva Braun]] and she is living with [[Adolf Hitler]] and four identical Aryan-looking boys.\n |LineColor       = #F4CA16\n}}\n}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nOn May 17, 2018, it was announced that [[Amazon Video]] had given the production a straight-to-series order for a first season consisting of ten episodes. The series was created by David Weil who was set to executive produce alongside [[Jordan Peele]], Tom Lesinski, Jenna Santoianni, and Win Rosenfeld. Weil was also expected to write for the series as well. Production companies involved with the series were slated to consist of [[Monkeypaw Productions]] and [[Sonar Entertainment]].<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/><ref>{{cite web|last=Maas|first=Jennifer|title=Amazon Orders Jordan Peele's Nazi-Hunting Show to Series|url=https://www.thewrap.com/amazon-orders-jordan-peeles-nazi-hunting-show-series/|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title=Jordan Peele-Produced Nazi Hunter Drama Ordered to Series at Amazon|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/jordan-peele-produced-nazi-hunter-drama-ordered-to-series-at-amazon-1202813713/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Jarvey|first=Natalie|title=Jordan Peele Nazi Drama Picked Up to Series at Amazon|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jordan-peele-nazi-drama-picked-up-series-at-amazon-1112812|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=May 17, 2018|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref> On August 7, 2018, it was announced that Nikki Toscano had joined the production as an executive producer and would also serve as co-showrunner alongside Weil.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='The Hunt': Nikki Toscano Joins Jordan Peele's Nazi Hunters Amazon Series As EP|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/the-hunt-nikki-toscano-jordan-peele-nazi-hunters-amazon-drama-series-executive-producer-showrunner-1202432730/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nOn December 13, 2018, it was reported that [[Logan Lerman]] was in talks for a lead role in the series, Jonah Heidelbaum.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title=Logan Lerman In Talks For Lead In Jordan Peele's 'The Hunt' Amazon Drama Series|url=https://deadline.com/2018/12/logan-lerman-in-talks-for-lead-in-jordan-peeles-the-hunt-amazon-drama-series-1202519900/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 13, 2018|accessdate=December 13, 2018}}</ref> On January 10, 2019, it was reported that [[Al Pacino]] was finalizing a deal for a starring role in the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fleming|first=Mike Jr|title=Al Pacino Poised To Make TV Series Starring Debut In 'The Hunt'|url=https://deadline.com/2019/01/al-pacino-television-series-star-debut-the-hunt-amazon-logan-lerman-1202532584/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 10, 2019|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> On February 7, 2019, it was reported that [[Jerrika Hinton]], [[Dylan Baker]], [[Lena Olin]], [[Greg Austin (actor)|Greg Austin]], [[Catherine Tate]], [[Tiffany Boone]], [[Saul Rubinek]], and [[Carol Kane]] were in various stages of negotiations to join the cast of the series.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sneider|first=Jeff|title=Exclusive: Jordan Peele's Cast for Amazon's 'The Hunt' Takes Shape|url=https://collider.com/jordan-peele-the-hunt-supporting-cast/|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|date=February 7, 2019|accessdate=February 7, 2019}}</ref> Four days later, it was announced that Boone had officially joined the cast.<ref>{{cite web|last=Petski|first=Denise|title='The Hunt': Tiffany Boone Cast In Jordan Peele's Amazon Drama Series|url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-hunt-tiffany-boone-cast-jordan-peeles-amazon-drama-series-1202554658/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 11, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref> [[Josh Radnor]] was cast in March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/the-hunt-josh-radnor-cast-jordan-peele-amazon-drama-series-1202567664/ |title='The Hunt': Josh Radnor To Co-Star In Jordan Peele's Amazon Drama Series |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]}}</ref> In April 2019, [[Kate Mulvany]], [[James LeGros]], [[Ebony Obsidian]],  Caleb Emery, Henry Hunter Hall and [[Jeannie Berlin]] joined the cast of the series, with Mulvany joining as a series regular.<ref>{{cite web|last=Day-Ramos|first=Dino|title='The Hunt' Adds Kate Mulvany As Series Regular, 5 More Join In Recurring Roles For Amazon Original|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/the-hunt-kate-mulvany-series-regular-amazon-jordan-peele-james-le-gros-ebony-obsidian-caleb-emery-henry-hunter-hall-jeannie-berline-david-weil-1202593377/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Hunters'' received polarizing reviews, with criticism for its tone and pacing and praise for its performances. The series has a 65% approval rating with 92 reviews on [[Rotten Tomatoes]], with an average rating of 6.21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/hunters_2020/s01|title=''Hunters'': Season 1 (2020) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the series a score of 55 out of 100 based on 37 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/hunters-2020/season-1?ref=hp|title=''Hunters'': Season 1|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe series has received some criticism from the [[Auschwitz-Birkenau State Museum]] due to inaccurate use of the [[Auschwitz Concentration Camp]]. The scene depicting prisoners being forced to participate in a game of human chess was called out as \"dangerous foolishness and caricature\". The museum was also concerned that the show \"welcomes future deniers\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/02/23/amazon-hunters-criticized-by-auschwitz-memorial-museum/|title=Amazon drama Hunters criticized by Auschwitz Memorial Museum|last=Cordero|first=Rosy|work=Entertainment Weekly|date=February 23, 2020|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsweek.com/amazon-hunters-david-weil-criticism-auschwitz-memorial-chess-nazis-1488714 |title=Amazon's 'Hunters' Creators Fictional Holocaust Atrocities Following Criticism From Auschwitz Memorial |work=Newsweek}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/hunters-stars-ponder-moral-question-at-center-nazi-hunter-amazon-drama-1280317 |title='Hunters' Stars Ponder the Moral Question at the Center of Their Nazi Hunter Amazon Drama|work=The Hollywood Reporter}}</ref> Director of the [[USC Shoah Foundation]] [[Stephen D. Smith]] heavily criticized the show and concluded that \"Amazon must not renew it for a second season.\"<ref>Smith, Stephen.  [https://jewishjournal.com/columnist-2/312011/shoah-foundation-director-amazon-must-cancel-hunters/ Shoah Foundation Director: Amazon Must Cancel \u2018Hunters.\u2019\"] ''Jewish Journal''.  12 March 2020.  13 March 2020.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|7456722}}\n*[https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=HBGkjmfIzAw Trailer]\n\n{{Amazon Video original series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hunters}}\n[[Category:2020s American drama television series]]\n[[Category:Amazon Video original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Nazi hunters in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Television series set in 1977]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:2020 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Fascism in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "GoodShoes1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eRecurring:actor added)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hunters_(2020_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Ilana Kloss", "text_new": "{{short description|South African tennis player, coach, and commissioner}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                  = Ilana Kloss\n| fullname              = Ilana Sheryl Kloss\n| image= Ilana Kloss 2009 US Open 02.jpg\n| country\n| residence             = New York City and Chicago\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1956|03|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place           = [[Johannesburg]], South Africa\n| height                =\n| turnedpro             = 1973\n| retired               =\n| plays                 = Left-handed\n| careerprizemoney      =\n| singlesrecord         =\n| singlestitles         =\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 19 (1976)\n| AustralianOpenresult  =\n| FrenchOpenresult      = 2R ([[1976 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1976]], [[1979 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1979]])\n| Wimbledonresult       = 3R ([[1975 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1975]], [[1976 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1976]], [[1978 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1978]])\n| USOpenresult          = 3R ([[1973 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1973]], [[1978 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1978]])\n| doublesrecord         =\n| doublestitles         = 19\n| highestdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = QF (1983)\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = SF (1976, 1979)\n| WimbledonDoublesresult  = SF ([[1976 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|1976]])\n| USOpenDoublesresult = '''W''' (1976)\n| mixedrecord         = \n| mixedtitles         = \n| AustralianOpenMixedresult   =\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult    = '''W''' (1976)\n| WimbledonMixedresult        =\n| USOpenMixedresult           =\n| OthertournamentsDoubles       = <!-- optional. If you fill in one of the next 3 parameters, fill in this as yes.-->\n}}\n\n'''Ilana Sheryl Kloss''' (born 22 March 1956) is a former professional [[tennis]] player, tennis coach, and commissioner of [[World TeamTennis]], since 2001.<ref name=wtt>{{cite web|title=Ilana Kloss|url=http://www.wtt.com/page.aspx?article_id=1787|publisher=WTT}}</ref> She was the World's No. 1 ranked doubles player in 1976, World No. 19 in singles in 1979.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.jewishsports.net/BioPages/Ilana-Kloss.htm \"Ilana Kloss\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKloss was born in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, and is Jewish.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=aOTWUl-9LQoC&pg=PA12&dq=Ilana+Kloss+jewish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOhezpz__aAhXly4MKHSn6B4IQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Ilana%20Kloss%20jewish&f=false ''Day by Day in Jewish Sports History'' - Bob Wechsler<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldtennismagazine.com/archives/11032 | title='The Greatest Jewish Tennis Players of All Time' Book Released | date=29 October 2014 | work=World Tennis Magazine | accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> \n\nKloss is the partner of [[Billie Jean King]], the US tennis player.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2006/4/pioneer.html |title=Portrait of a Pioneer: a Billie Jean King Documentary &#124; TV Show Recaps, Celebrity Interviews & News About & For Gay, Lesbian & Bisexual Women |publisher=AfterEllen.com |date=26 April 2006 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518082930/http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2006/4/pioneer.html |archive-date=18 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The two of them became minority owners of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] baseball team in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/dodgers-welcome-billie-jean-king-ilana-kloss/c-295526684|title=Addition of King, Kloss sends 'strong message'|first=Ken|last=Gurnick|work=MLB.com|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nBefore turning professional, she won the juniors singles title at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in 1972.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/jewishlistsphysi00gree <!-- quote=Ilana Kloss jewish. --> ''The Jewish lists: physicists and generals, actors and writers, and hundreds ...'' - Martin Harry Greenberg<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She won the SA doubles title with [[Linky Boshoff]] in 1973, 1975, and 1977.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=bDBQAQAAIAAJ&q=Ilana+Kloss+jewish&dq=Ilana+Kloss+jewish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOhezpz__aAhXly4MKHSn6B4IQ6AEILzAB ''Jewish Affairs''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She also played in the [[Maccabiah Games]] in Israel, winning gold medals in both the women\u2019s doubles and the mixed doubles in the [[1973 Maccabiah Games]], and winning a silver medal in mixed doubles in the [[1977 Maccabiah Games]].<ref>[https://www.jta.org/1985/07/26/archive/at-the-maccabiah-games-u-s-wins-the-most-medals-with-246-israel-comes-in-second-with-217 At the Maccabiah Games: U.S. Wins the Most Medals with 246; Israel Comes in Second with 217 | Jewish Telegraphic Agency<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.jta.org/1977/07/22/archive/israel-basketball-team-loses-out-to-underdog-u-s-squad-at-10th-maccabiah Israel Basketball Team Loses out to Underdog U.S. Squad at 10th Maccabiah | Jewish Telegraphic Agency<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatennisflorida.usta.com/Florida/Global/News/Adults%20Seniors/2008_09/6618937_Seeking_Jewish_Tennis_Players_to_Represent_the_United_States_.aspx |title=Seeking Jewish Tennis Players to Represent the United States &#124; Adults-Seniors \u2013 News &#124; USTA Florida |publisher=Usatennisflorida.usta.com |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, she won [[U.S. Open (tennis)|US Open]] juniors singles title.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> She was the youngest No. 1 player in South African history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://2010.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/jrchamps.html |title=US Open junior champions |access-date=24 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711143157/http://2010.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/jrchamps.html |archive-date=11 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Jews in Sports\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewsinsports.org/profile.asp?sport=tennis&ID=79|title=Kloss, Ilana|publisher=Jews in Sports|accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref> In 1973, she won the title in [[Cincinnati Masters|Cincinnati]] with Pat Walkden, defeating [[Evonne Goolagong]] and [[Janet Young (tennis)|Janet Young]] in the final.\n\nKloss was ranked No. 1 in the world in doubles and No. 19 in singles in 1976. That year, she won doubles titles at the US Open, the [[Rome Masters|Italian Open]], the US Clay Courts, the [[Hamburg Masters|German Open]], the British Hard Courts Championship, and [[Hilton Head]], as well as the mixed doubles title at the French Open.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" /> Linky Boshoff was her most frequent doubles partner.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" /> In 1977 she won the Canadian and German championships and the British clay court championship.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" />\n\nIn 1999, Kloss won the US Open doubles and mixed doubles championship on the 35-and-over tour.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" />\n\n===Federation Cup===\nFrom 1973 until 1977, Kloss was a member of the [[South Africa Fed Cup team|South African team]] that competed in the [[Fed Cup|Federation Cup]]. She compiled a 12\u20135 win/loss record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player profile \u2013 Ilana Kloss |url=https://www.fedcup.com/en/players/player.aspx?id=800175600 |website=www.fedcup.com |publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] (ITF)}}</ref>\n\n===Halls of Fame===\n\nKloss, who is Jewish, was inducted into the US National Jewish Sports Hall of Fame in 2006. She was inducted into the International Jewish Sports Hall of Fame in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===World Team Tennis===\nKloss joined the [[San Francisco Golden Gaters]] [[World TeamTennis|WTT]] team in 1974,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chatoian|first1=Ralph|title=An Analysis of the Pro Tennis League|newspaper=[[Marin Independent Journal|Daily Independent Journal]]|location=[[San Rafael, California]]|page=28|date=23 April 1974}}</ref> and reached the WTT Finals with the team in 1975.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mulligan|first1=Stephen|year=2011|chapter=3. 1971\u20131975|title=Were You There?: Over 300 Wonderful, Weird, an Wacky Moments from the Pittsburgh Civic/Mellon Arena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1qFcgbuVVYC|publisher=RoseDog Books|pages=62\u201364|isbn=978-1-4349-8552-1|lccn=2011278129|accessdate=19 August 2014 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> She left the Golden Gaters prior to the 1976 season to team in order to fully participate in [[clay court|clay-court]] [[tournament|tournaments]] in [[Europe]] which conflicted with the WTT schedule.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chatoian|first1=Ralph|title=Golden Gaters Add Some French to Arsenal|newspaper=[[Marin Independent Journal|Daily Independent Journal]]|location=[[San Rafael, California]]|page=24|date=9 March 1976}}</ref> Kloss returned to the Golden Gaters for the 1978 season. In 1983, she coached the Chicago Fyre to a WTT Championship and was named Coach of the Year. In 1985, Kloss was a player and coach for the Miami Beach Breakers, and became vice-president of WTT in 1987 and executive director in 1991. Since 2001, she has been the chief executive officer and commissioner of World Team Tennis.<ref name=wtt/>\n\n==Grand Slam tournament finals==\n\n===Women's doubles: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:35px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Championship \n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:130px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win || [[1976 US Open (tennis)|1976]] || [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] || Clay || {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Linky Boshoff]] || {{flagicon|URS}} [[Olga Morozova]] <br> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Virginia Wade]] ||  6\u20131, 6\u20134\n|}\n\n===Mixed doubles: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:35px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Championship \n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:130px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ebc2af;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win || [[1976 French Open|1976]] || French Open || Clay || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Kim Warwick]] ||   {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Linky Boshoff]] <br> {{flagicon|RHO}} [[Colin Dowdeswell]]  || 5\u20137, 7\u20136, 6\u20132\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Jews in sports#Tennis|List of select Jewish tennis players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Fed Cup player}}\n* [http://www.jewishsports.org/jewishsports/detail.asp?sp=182 Jewish Sports Hall of Fame profile]\n\n\n{{Wimbledon girls' singles champions}}\n{{US Open girls' singles champions}}\n{{US Open women's doubles champions}}\n{{French Open mixed doubles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kloss, Ilana}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jewish tennis players]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from South Africa]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Johannesburg]]\n[[Category:South African female tennis players]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n[[Category:US Open (tennis) junior champions]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:Lesbian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:LGBT tennis players]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in girls' singles]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1973 Maccabiah Games]]\n[[Category:Competitors at the 1977 Maccabiah Games]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games medalists in tennis]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games gold medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:Maccabiah Games silver medalists for South Africa]]\n[[Category:White South African people]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers executives]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers owners]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball executives]]\n[[Category:US Open (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:French Open champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African tennis player, coach, and commissioner}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n| name                  = Ilana Kloss\n| fullname              = Ilana Sheryl Kloss\n| image= Ilana Kloss 2009 US Open 02.jpg\n| country\n| residence             = New York City and Chicago\n| birth_date            = {{birth date and age|1956|03|22|df=y}}\n| birth_place           = [[Johannesburg]], South Africa\n| height                =\n| turnedpro             = 1973\n| retired               =\n| plays                 = Left-handed\n| careerprizemoney      =\n| singlesrecord         =\n| singlestitles         =\n| highestsinglesranking = No. 19 (1976)\n| AustralianOpenresult  =\n| FrenchOpenresult      = 2R ([[1976 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1976]], [[1979 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1979]])\n| Wimbledonresult       = 3R ([[1975 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1975]], [[1976 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1976]], [[1978 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1978]])\n| USOpenresult          = 3R ([[1973 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1973]], [[1978 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1978]])\n| doublesrecord         =\n| doublestitles         = 19\n| highestdoublesranking = \n| AustralianOpenDoublesresult = QF (1983)\n| FrenchOpenDoublesresult = SF (1976, 1979)\n| WimbledonDoublesresult  = SF (1976)\n| USOpenDoublesresult = '''W''' (1976)\n| mixedrecord         = \n| mixedtitles         = \n| AustralianOpenMixedresult   =\n| FrenchOpenMixedresult    = '''W'''  1976\n| WimbledonMixedresult        =\n| USOpenMixedresult           =\n| OthertournamentsDoubles       = <!-- optional. If you fill in one of the next 3 parameters, fill in this as yes.-->\n}}\n\n'''Ilana Sheryl Kloss''' (born 22 March 1956) is a former professional tennis player, tennis coach, and commissioner of [[World TeamTennis]], since 2001.<ref name=wtt>{{cite web|title=Ilana Kloss|url=http://www.wtt.com/page.aspx?article_id=1787|publisher=WTT}}</ref> She was the World's No. 1 ranked doubles player in 1976, World No. 19 in singles in 1979.<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://www.jewishsports.net/BioPages/Ilana-Kloss.htm \"Ilana Kloss\"<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nKloss was born in [[Johannesburg]], South Africa, and is Jewish.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=aOTWUl-9LQoC&pg=PA12&dq=Ilana+Kloss+jewish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOhezpz__aAhXly4MKHSn6B4IQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q=Ilana%20Kloss%20jewish&f=false ''Day by Day in Jewish Sports History'' - Bob Wechsler<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldtennismagazine.com/archives/11032 | title='The Greatest Jewish Tennis Players of All Time' Book Released | date=29 October 2014 | work=World Tennis Magazine | accessdate=6 January 2019}}</ref> \n\nKloss is the partner of [[Billie Jean King]], the US tennis player.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2006/4/pioneer.html |title=Portrait of a Pioneer: a Billie Jean King Documentary &#124; TV Show Recaps, Celebrity Interviews & News About & For Gay, Lesbian & Bisexual Women |publisher=AfterEllen.com |date=26 April 2006 |accessdate=11 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110518082930/http://www.afterellen.com/TV/2006/4/pioneer.html |archive-date=18 May 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The two of them became minority owners of the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] baseball team in September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/dodgers-welcome-billie-jean-king-ilana-kloss/c-295526684|title=Addition of King, Kloss sends 'strong message'|first=Ken|last=Gurnick|work=MLB.com|date=21 September 2018|accessdate=31 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Tennis career==\nBefore turning professional, she won the juniors singles title at [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] in 1972.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/jewishlistsphysi00gree <!-- quote=Ilana Kloss jewish. --> ''The Jewish lists: physicists and generals, actors and writers, and hundreds ...'' - Martin Harry Greenberg<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She won the SA doubles title with [[Linky Boshoff]] in 1973, 1975, and 1977.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=bDBQAQAAIAAJ&q=Ilana+Kloss+jewish&dq=Ilana+Kloss+jewish&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOhezpz__aAhXly4MKHSn6B4IQ6AEILzAB ''Jewish Affairs''<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> She also played in the [[Maccabiah Games]] in Israel, winning gold medals in both the women\u2019s doubles and the mixed doubles in the [[1973 Maccabiah Games]], and winning a silver medal in mixed doubles in the [[1977 Maccabiah Games]].<ref>[https://www.jta.org/1985/07/26/archive/at-the-maccabiah-games-u-s-wins-the-most-medals-with-246-israel-comes-in-second-with-217 At the Maccabiah Games: U.S. Wins the Most Medals with 246; Israel Comes in Second with 217 | Jewish Telegraphic Agency<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>[https://www.jta.org/1977/07/22/archive/israel-basketball-team-loses-out-to-underdog-u-s-squad-at-10th-maccabiah Israel Basketball Team Loses out to Underdog U.S. Squad at 10th Maccabiah | Jewish Telegraphic Agency<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usatennisflorida.usta.com/Florida/Global/News/Adults%20Seniors/2008_09/6618937_Seeking_Jewish_Tennis_Players_to_Represent_the_United_States_.aspx |title=Seeking Jewish Tennis Players to Represent the United States &#124; Adults-Seniors \u2013 News &#124; USTA Florida |publisher=Usatennisflorida.usta.com |date=22 September 2008 |accessdate=11 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, she won [[U.S. Open (tennis)|US Open]] juniors singles title.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> She was the youngest No. 1 player in South African history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://2010.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/jrchamps.html |title=US Open junior champions |access-date=24 February 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110711143157/http://2010.usopen.org/en_US/about/history/jrchamps.html |archive-date=11 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Jews in Sports\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewsinsports.org/profile.asp?sport=tennis&ID=79|title=Kloss, Ilana|publisher=Jews in Sports|accessdate=5 February 2014}}</ref> In 1973, she won the title in [[Cincinnati Masters|Cincinnati]] with Pat Walkden, defeating [[Evonne Goolagong]] and [[Janet Young (tennis)|Janet Young]] in the final.\n\nKloss was ranked No. 1 in the world in doubles and No. 19 in singles in 1976. That year, she won doubles titles at the US Open, the [[Rome Masters|Italian Open]], the US Clay Courts, the [[Hamburg Masters|German Open]], the British Hard Courts Championship, and [[Hilton Head]], as well as the mixed doubles title at the French Open.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" /> Linky Boshoff was her most frequent doubles partner.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" /> In 1977 she won the Canadian and German championships and the British clay court championship.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" />\n\nIn 1999, Kloss won the US Open doubles and mixed doubles championship on the 35-and-over tour.<ref name=\"Jews in Sports\" />\n\n===Federation Cup===\nFrom 1973 until 1977, Kloss was a member of the [[South Africa Fed Cup team|South African team]] that competed in the [[Fed Cup|Federation Cup]]. She compiled a 12\u20135 win/loss record.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player profile \u2013 Ilana Kloss |url=https://www.fedcup.com/en/players/player.aspx?id=800175600 |website=www.fedcup.com |publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] (ITF)}}</ref>\n\n===Halls of Fame===\n\nKloss, who is Jewish, was inducted into the US National Jewish Sports Hall of Fame in 2006. She was inducted into the International Jewish Sports Hall of Fame in 2010.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n===World Team Tennis===\nKloss joined the [[San Francisco Golden Gaters]] [[World TeamTennis|WTT]] team in 1974,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chatoian|first1=Ralph|title=An Analysis of the Pro Tennis League|newspaper=[[Marin Independent Journal|Daily Independent Journal]]|location=[[San Rafael, California]]|page=28|date=23 April 1974}}</ref> and reached the WTT Finals with the team in 1975.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mulligan|first1=Stephen|year=2011|chapter=3. 1971\u20131975|title=Were You There?: Over 300 Wonderful, Weird, an Wacky Moments from the Pittsburgh Civic/Mellon Arena|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1qFcgbuVVYC|publisher=RoseDog Books|pages=62\u201364|isbn=978-1-4349-8552-1|lccn=2011278129|accessdate=19 August 2014 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> She left the Golden Gaters prior to the 1976 season to team in order to fully participate in [[clay court|clay-court]] [[tournament|tournaments]] in [[Europe]] which conflicted with the WTT schedule.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chatoian|first1=Ralph|title=Golden Gaters Add Some French to Arsenal|newspaper=[[Marin Independent Journal|Daily Independent Journal]]|location=[[San Rafael, California]]|page=24|date=9 March 1976}}</ref> Kloss returned to the Golden Gaters for the 1978 season. In 1983, she coached the Chicago Fyre to a WTT Championship and was named Coach of the Year. In 1985, Kloss was a player and coach for the Miami Beach Breakers, and became vice-president of WTT in 1987 and executive director in 1991. Since 2001, she has been the chief executive officer and commissioner of World Team Tennis.<ref name=wtt/>\n\n==Grand Slam tournament finals==\n\n===Women's doubles: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:35px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Championship \n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:130px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win || [[1976 US Open (tennis)|1976]] || [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] || Clay || {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Linky Boshoff]] || {{flagicon|URS}} [[Olga Morozova]] <br> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Virginia Wade]] ||  6\u20131, 6\u20134\n|}\n\n===Mixed doubles: 1 (1 title)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:35px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Championship \n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:160px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:130px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ebc2af;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win || [[1976 French Open|1976]] || French Open || Clay || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Kim Warwick]] ||   {{flagicon|RSA|1928}} [[Linky Boshoff]] <br> {{flagicon|RHO}} [[Colin Dowdeswell]]  || 5\u20137, 7\u20136, 6\u20132\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Jews in sports#Tennis|List of select Jewish tennis players]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Fed Cup player}}\n* [http://www.jewishsports.org/jewishsports/detail.asp?sp=182 Jewish Sports Hall of Fame profile]\n\n\n{{Wimbledon girls' singles champions}}\n{{US Open girls' singles champions}}\n{{US Open women's doubles champions}}\n{{French Open mixed doubles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kloss, Ilana}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Jewish tennis players]]\n[[Category:LGBT Jews]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from South Africa]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Johannesburg]]\n[[Category:South African female tennis players]]\n[[Category:South African Jews]]\n[[Category:US Open (tennis) junior champions]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:Lesbian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:LGBT tennis players]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in mixed doubles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) ch